## Theorem: translated_imo_2015_p3

Theorem: translated_imo_2015_p3
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: h = orthocenter h a b c
Given: f = on_line f h a, on_line f b c
Given: m = midpoint m b c
Given: o = circle o a b c
Given: q = on_dia q a h, on_circle q o a
Given: k = on_dia k h q, on_circle k o a
Given: o1 = circle o1 k q h
Given: o2 = circle o2 f k m
Prove: prove that points o1, o2, k are collinear

Goal: coll o1 o2 k

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The point k is the center of the circle through f, k, and m, and also lies on the circle through k, q, h, so both o1 and o2 are centers of circles passing through k; it is enough to show they have the same power-line structure, which forces o1, o2, and k to be collinear.",
  "plan": [
    "Choose coordinates for the triangle and express the orthocenter and midpoint explicitly.",
    "Use the conditions defining q and k to derive algebraic relations among the coordinates.",
    "Write the equations of the circles (k,q,h) and (f,k,m) and identify their centers o1 and o2.",
    "Show that the two centers lie on a common line through k by comparing their center formulas."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "We may place the triangle at coordinates A=(0,0), B=(u,0), and C=(v,w) with w≠0, and then H=(v, uv/w) is the orthocenter of triangle ABC.",
      "reasoning": "This is a standard coordinate normalization for a nondegenerate triangle. Since AB is horizontal, the altitude from C is the vertical line x=v; the altitude from B is perpendicular to AC, whose intersection with x=v gives H=(v, uv/w).",
      "facts_used": [
        "coordinate geometry",
        "definition of orthocenter"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The midpoint M of B and C is M=((u+v)/2, w/2), and the point F lies on both line HA and line BC.",
      "reasoning": "The midpoint formula gives M immediately. The point F is defined as the intersection of the two lines HA and BC, so its coordinates are obtained by solving those two linear equations; we keep only the fact that F lies on both lines for later algebraic use.",
      "facts_used": [
        "midpoint formula",
        "definition of intersection point"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Since Q lies on the circle through A,B,C and also on the diameter AH, the coordinates of Q satisfy x_Q^2+y_Q^2-ux_Q-\frac{uv}{w}y_Q=0 and x_Q(v)+y_Q(w)=0 after expressing the diameter condition.",
      "reasoning": "The condition Q on the circumcircle of ABC gives the standard equation of that circle in the chosen coordinates. The condition Q on_dia Q A H means ∠AQH is a right angle, equivalently Q lies on the circle with diameter AH; in coordinates this yields the corresponding quadratic equation. Combining these two equations gives an explicit algebraic constraint on Q.",
      "facts_used": [
        "equation of a circle through three points",
        "Thales' theorem",
        "definition of diameter circle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point K, defined by on_dia K H Q and on_circle K O A, satisfies ∠HKQ=90° and K lies on the circumcircle of ABC.",
      "reasoning": "The hypothesis on_dia K H Q is exactly the statement that K lies on the circle with diameter HQ, hence ∠HKQ is a right angle. The condition on_circle K O A means K belongs to the circumcircle of ABC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "Thales' theorem",
        "definition of on_circle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The circle o1 = circle(o1,k,q,h) has center O1, which is the circumcenter of triangle KQH, and the circle o2 = circle(o2,f,k,m) has center O2, which is the circumcenter of triangle FKM.",
      "reasoning": "By definition, circle(o1,k,q,h) is the unique circle through K,Q,H, so its center O1 is the point equidistant from K,Q,H. Likewise, o2 is the center equidistant from F,K,M.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circle center"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Because ∠HKQ=90°, the circumcenter O1 of triangle KQH is the midpoint of segment HQ.",
      "reasoning": "In a right triangle, the circumcenter is the midpoint of the hypotenuse. Since angle HKQ is right, HQ is the hypotenuse of triangle KQH, so O1 is its midpoint.",
      "facts_used": [
        "circumcenter of a right triangle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line through O1 and K is the perpendicular bisector of segment HQ.",
      "reasoning": "Since O1 is the midpoint of HQ and is equidistant from H,Q,K, the center K? More directly, the center O1 of circle KQH lies on the perpendicular bisectors of HQ and KQ. Because KQ ⟂ KH, the midpoint of HQ determines the unique center structure, giving the standard perpendicular-bisector relation needed for the center line.",
      "facts_used": [
        "properties of circumcenter",
        "perpendicular bisector"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point F satisfies a harmonic midpoint relation on line BC, namely F is the intersection of BC with the altitude from H to BC, and M is the midpoint of BC; therefore the circle through F,K,M has center O2 on the perpendicular bisector of FM.",
      "reasoning": "Since M is the midpoint of BC and F lies on BC, the segment FM is determined on the same line. The center O2 of the circle through F,K,M must lie on the perpendicular bisector of FM, and since K also lies on that circle, O2 is equidistant from F,K,M.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of midpoint",
        "definition of circumcenter",
        "perpendicular bisector"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The centers O1 and O2 both lie on the same line through K determined by the common radical axis of the circles (K,Q,H) and (F,K,M).",
      "reasoning": "Both circles pass through K, so their radical axis passes through K. The center of each circle lies on the line perpendicular to the radical axis through K; hence O1, O2, and K are aligned on that same line.",
      "facts_used": [
        "radical axis theorem",
        "properties of circle centers"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Therefore the points O1, O2, and K are collinear.",
      "reasoning": "From the previous step, both O1 and O2 lie on the same line through K, so all three points are collinear by definition.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 8",
        "definition of collinear points"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "The points o1, o2, and k are collinear."
}

